Text.Value: Sound the horn, then.
This drow is no fool - she knows the smart thing is to be patient, starve us out.
She tricked the location out of me. It was a mistake - but I mean to make up for it.
Well. There's nothing for it, now - a fight it will have to be.

EditorData.NodeContext: Fatalistic - he usually respects the gods but praying has availed him nothing. He appreciates your will to act.

Text.Value: I think... I think that's the last of them.

EditorData.NodeContext: Elated but trembling, in shock - he'd hoped they would survive but never fully believed it.

Text.Value: Don't look for reasons - it's nothing personal.
Their drow leader found the grove. I couldn't stop it - I'm sorry.
So... what? We're to be bait for this drow? Gods above, I...
But perhaps...
Gods above, you're alive. A little light, just as the day seems darkest.

EditorData.NodeContext: He's relieved to see you, but warning of the impending attack - player might just have jumped out of the frying pan and into the fire.

Text.Value: But she'll find you waiting, too.
I didn't turn on anyone. I look out for myself.
I'd sooner start this on our terms than theirs.
Every ounce of oil that we could spare has been buried out in front of the gate.
Gods, it's done. It's over. Just... just give me a moment.

EditorData.NodeContext: His first true sign of vulnerability - he's presented a facade of calm and control to the people he leads, and he's letting it go for just a moment.

Text.Value: Take heart. My god is watching over us.
Take me through the plan again.
We've spotted goblins in the woods - what happened at their camp?
You haven't - and so we place our faith in you instead.

EditorData.NodeContext: He's settling into state of fatalistic resolve - he's tried everything else to keep these people safe, but there's no reasoning with goblins.

Text.Value: We threw them back once. If you're with us... perhaps we can do it again.
You've fortified the place well - we're ready for them.
The horn - damn thing's loud as thunder. It'll give our people a chance to take shelter, too.
I suspect we'll need it before the day is done. The fact is, we cannot withstand a siege.
Why? For the glory of the Absolute, of course!
Gods! You have a habit of turning up where you're least expected - but no less welcome for that.
She'll take the bait - and with the defences ready, we'll win the day.
How did you -
We're ready to head to your camp - are you?
Surely there's a better option.
Make what preparations you deem necessary, and then sound the horn. Let's have this done.
We'll blow the horn to draw them in, and pray our fire-arrows strike true.
Simple. This grove belongs to the Absolute now.
See to your preparations and then sound the horn. Let's have this done.
Trust me - she thinks we're on the same side.
A mistake? It's a damned - gods damn it, we're not ready for this.
When the Blade told me of what you'd done, I was loathe to believe it.
Mrag. It... it doesn't matter now, I suppose. You have nothing to apologise for.
I am just here for the show. I want to see you all die.
I know we can make a stand here. We have to. Your help will be welcome.
Relax - this is a trap, and now she's walking right into it.
I'd given you up for dead at the goblin camp - I'm damn glad to be wrong.
We need to thin the goblin numbers quickly if we're to have any chance of survival.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim - the next few lines are him explaining a course of action he'd rather not take, but emphasising that there's no choice.

Text.Value: With you? You misunderstand - I'm with them.
I wish it were as complicated as all that.

EditorData.NodeContext: Nervous and afraid, but still a little humour - their plan is a foolish one.

Text.Value: Well, are you ready? Are we?

EditorData.NodeContext: A hint of impatience, but acknowledging that you're the one calling the shots.

Text.Value: The goblins are coming - and they're led by a drow.
Not just yet.
Our trap? I can't help but feel that we're the ones backed into a corner.
If it's to be battle, sooner is better than later. We need to ready ourselves and goad this drow into attacking.
We have the barricades - just not the warriors to man them. If we're to survive, we'll need to thin the goblin numbers quickly.
From what little I've learned of goblins, they won't resist an invitation like that.
But... if you say you're a match for this drow, I suppose that's the best chance we have.
I'm glad to see his fears weren't as bad as he imagined.
I mean to prick at her pride - give her no choice but to be stupid. Sound the horn - let's have this done.
Hah. What I have is no choice - we need to thin their numbers quickly if we're to survive.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim - the next few lines are him explaining a course of action he'd rather not take, but emphasising that there's no choice.

Text.Value: We'll get through this, I swear to you.
But what happened? We've seen them massing in the woods.
If it must be bloodshed after all, I'm glad to have you with us.
As we'll ever be.
Do what you must, but quickly. Once you sound the horn, they'll come running.

RuleGroup.RuleString: CLERIC_BHAAL or CLERIC_MYRKUL or PALADIN_BHAAL or PALADIN_MYRKUL

Text.Value: I follow a god of death. That requires the occasional offering.
I don't... Oh, gods.

EditorData.NodeContext: It takes him a moment to realise what he's being told - that the player has betrayed them and sided with the goblins.

Text.Value: I met the drow leading them - and led her here.
Guards! Guards, help!
I want to see droves, piles, heaps of dead. I want to climb a corpsed mountain.
You've turned on us? Hells, why?
Believe me, I've prayed to find one - but the gods have seen fit to stay out of this.

EditorData.NodeContext: Firm. He's reached a decision, even if it is a dangeorus one.

Text.Value: I... don't know. I'm sorry. I wanted to save you, but it seems I'm too weak.
Just give the word.
A challenge for all to witness. She'll have a hard time resisting.
Truly? Hells, I didn't expect her to... We were almost ready to leave.

EditorData.NodeContext: Quietly - he's usually polite and pragmatic, but you've just confirmed that they're facing overwhelming odds. Rare moment of vulnerabilty before the mask is restored in the next node.

Text.Value: You led the drow here? By the Nine Hells, why?
No point waiting around then. What do you need?
Excellent - lead the way.
The horn. If you seek to draw her in, that damned thing's loud as thunder. It'll give our people a chance to take shelter, too.
Take heart. My god is watching over us.
Your courage is catching, it seems. Or perhaps I've finally lost my reason.
No - you can't! I trusted you!

EditorData.NodeContext: Upset, the player has given up the entire tiefling grove for slaughter.

Text.Value: You can understand why we've had to be cautious at the gates.
Yes - let's go.
It's who I am. Sin incarnate.
I can't tell if that's a really good plan or an awful one.
Not yet - I need more time.
Good. She's expecting to find us weak and desperate - and she's not wrong.
Do you have a plan?
Traitor. The Blade now comes for you.
Of course it's personal.
They are my horde. Together, we shall feast upon you.
If this is what it has come to, then... so be it. You'll need to draw her attention.

Synopsis: Zevlor is tense - he's awaiting a long-expected attack on the grove, and the player is likely here to confirm it or perhaps even strike the first blow against him. Zevlor's usual tone is all stiff upper-lip, but at certain points we'll see the cracks start to form.
